  "prompt": "What are things you realized only in your senior year of college?",
  "response": "Ah, senior year. That bittersweet time of reflection and impending adulthood. Here are some things I \"realized\" (or at least truly *understood*) in my senior year of college, based on my experience and observations:\n\n**Academically & Career-Wise:**\n\n*   **Networking isn't just about getting a job, it's about building relationships:** Freshman me thought networking was solely about cold-emailing and collecting business cards. Senior year me realized it's about genuine connection, shared interests, and long-term rapport. It's about people *remembering* you as a person, not just a resume.\n*   **Your major doesn't define you, but your skills do:** I panicked less about not having a \"perfectly aligned\" job and focused more on the skills I had developed through my classes, extracurriculars, and personal projects. Those transferable skills were more valuable than the major label.\n*   **Professors are people, too!** I actually started going to office hours *not* just when I was struggling, but to discuss ideas and learn more about their fields.  I realized they're a valuable resource beyond just grades.\n*   **It's okay not to have a five-year plan:** So much pressure is put on students to have it all figured out. Senior year taught me it was perfectly acceptable (and probably healthier) to be open to opportunities and adapt as I learned more about myself.\n*   **Learning never stops (and it becomes *more* valuable):**  College is great, but the real learning begins after graduation.  You start applying what you learned in real-world scenarios, and constantly need to learn new things to keep up.\n\n**Socially & Personally:**\n\n*   **Some friendships are seasonal, and that's okay:**  People drift apart, especially during major life transitions.  It doesn't mean those friendships weren't important; it just means life has taken you in different directions. Cherish the memories, but don't force connections that no longer serve you.\n*   **Self-care is not a luxury, it's a necessity:** I finally understood that burning the candle at both ends wasn't a badge of honor, but a recipe for burnout.  Making time for activities I enjoyed became a non-negotiable.\n*   **Your college experience is unique to you, and that's what makes it special:** Comparing myself to others and their \"highlight reel\" experiences was pointless.  My college journey was filled with its own set of unique challenges, triumphs, and moments that shaped me.\n*   **The real world is a lot more ambiguous than textbooks:** College has right and wrong answers. Adulthood? Not so much. Learning to navigate uncertainty and make decisions with imperfect information is key.\n*   **Time flies (duh, but REALLY fast):** Senior year went by in a blur. I regretted not taking more risks, not saying yes to more opportunities, and not appreciating the little moments more.  The \"college bubble\" is a special time; soak it in.\n*   **\"Adulting\" is a skill that you can acquire:** Things that previously seemed insurmountable, like figuring out taxes or navigating healthcare, slowly became manageable through research, asking for help, and trial and error.\n*   **Your network is going to be a key ingredient to your success:** I realized that building relationships with not just professors, but also with the staff at college, and my fellow classmates would continue to be helpful in my future endeavors.\n\n**Overall:**\n\n*   **College is a privilege, not a guarantee of success:** A degree opens doors, but it doesn't guarantee a job or happiness. Hard work, persistence, and a willingness to learn are still essential.\n*   **You're more resilient than you think:** College throws a lot at you \u2013 academic pressure, social anxieties, financial stress.  Surviving (and hopefully thriving) proves you're capable of handling whatever life throws your way.\n*   **Gratitude is essential:** Being thankful for the opportunities, experiences, and people that shaped your college journey makes the transition to the \"real world\" a little less daunting.\n\nThese are just a few of the realizations I had in my senior year.  Everyone's experience is different, but hopefully, these resonate and offer some perspective. Good luck with your final year!\n",
